    Beautiful and long beach
    My Khe is the central beach of Da Nang city. It's a long and sandy beach, pretty wide. Many hotels line it, just across a busy street. There're many free parts, as well some where's a bar and where you can rent sunbeds. Water is shallow for long, usually with waves. Try to get up early one day before sunrise, as the beach is east oriented. Apart beautiful scenery of the rising sun, you'll enjoy many locals around swimming, practicing tai-chi, jogging, exercising.
    Visited January 2024
    Traveled with family

  • arpitam
    Gurugram (Gurgaon), India931 contributions
    Not to be missed if you are in Danang
    A very long stretch of clean and wide beach with lots of gaming and fun activities options. People start their day with a yoga or Tai Chi session right at the beach. This is such peaceful sight to behold just when the sun rises across the horizon of Vietnam sea. The sea side promenade is very well maintained and equipped with exercise machines for the daily use of residents / tourist. Many people are seen cycling along the beach. As the day progresses team of visitors start to arrive. Active beach volleyball is very common. Generally the beach is absolutely safe for bathing with small waves. Surfers gather at the places with more waves. There are numerous beach side shacks with variety of food and drinks for all types of visitors.
    Visited April 2024
    Traveled with family
    Written April 3, 2024

A coastal gem for relaxation and adventure
May 2024 • Couples
My Khe Beach exceeded our expectations with its pristine white sand, crystal clear water, and gentle waves. It's a haven for swimmers, sunbathers, and water sports enthusiasts alike. We particularly enjoyed the excellent surfing conditions and watching the local fishermen cast their nets at dawn.

Located in the heart of Da Nang, My Khe Beach offers easy access to a plethora of restaurants serving fresh seafood and traditional Vietnamese cuisine. The diverse culture of the area adds another layer of interest to the experience.

We were captivated by the stunning sunrises over the South China Sea. Whether you're seeking relaxation or an active beach vacation, My Khe Beach provides a memorable escape.

Y4Travel
Piketberg, South Africa217 contributions
If you want to be in a beach town, stay in Danang. You can always take daytrips to Hoi An, which is only 29km away. Hoi An also has a few nice beaches about 5km away, An Bang (very touristy), Lonely beach (very nice and cheaper), and Coconut beach (you will have the whole beach to yourself). Are you travelling with kids? We rented scooters for the week, and travelled between the 2 towns (we stayed in both). The distance between Danang and Hue is about 100km one way. So put a whole day aside if you are not sleeping over in Hue. (you are obviously going to stop along the way to take in the scenery and take pictures). Also Hai Van Pass has lots of twists and turns, if you are travelling by scooter and are not an experienced motorcycle driver, beware of trucks, etc. But still worth it, very beautiful. I have a contact in Danang for renting scooters. Just message me.

Joseph M
5 contributions
I've just moved to Da Nang to work here for a year, and had been really looking forward to doing lots of swimming! However, there seem to be "no swimming" signs pretty much down the entirety of the beach? There are only a few small sections where swimming is permitted, and so these tiny areas are super crowded and it's impossible to relax and swim. The sections seem to have been chosen arbitrarily and even if I venture out a few metres from the invisible line in the water, an overzealous lifeguard uses his whistle and waves me back in. Does anyone know the reasoning behind this? There are no boats moored, and the water is very shallow even in the no swimming areas.
Peter C
Helensburgh, UK217 contributions
As far as I am aware, the 'no swimming zones' are more prevalent at this time of year due to weather conditions, which result in large amounts of debris and more importantly, 'under tows' or 'rip currents' and I certainly noticed the latter off My Khe beach on my visit in September. The tides also create 'hidden gullies' which can suddenly put you out of your depth. Hopefully the areas will become less prevalent as the seasons change, but in the meantime, rely on the lifeguards.
